<br>
&quot; On the eve of the Festival of Innoruuk, cases of strong spirits, specially brewed by the Dwarves, laced with a sleeping potion concocted by the shamaness were delivered to Neriak. In the middle of the night when the last of the guards was drunk and in a deep sleep, the band of rescuers snuck in.<br>
<br>
The dwarven rogues emerged into the lair of children with torches sending them into a terrific chorus of screams, sounding a loud alarm echoing through the caverns. They set upon the children, picking the locks off their bonds as quickly as possible. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, Vri’dril and his men where there, having just arrived from another trip. Seeing the chaos, he ordered the children to be killed as fast as possible. Kate and the rest arrived in time to fight his men. <br>
<br>
Malaeliu was back in the temple in Third Gate pacing and praying for guidance. She was answered with a cold chill of laughter and screaming children. She tore the symbol of Innoruuk off her neck and threw it upon the holy altar, absolving her devotion to the Prince of Hate. <br>
<br>
She rushed into the commons and was shocked to hear silence. Running into the lair, the vision of carnage was unbelievable… hundred and hundreds of scorched bodies. Vri’dril had ordered his wizards to destroy the intruders and all the evidence. <br>
<br>
Picking through the bodies carefully, she saw the Shamaness. She tried to heal her but Kate was far gone. She took her Mace and her beads from her neck and put them in her bag, vowing to find her family to return these to.<br>
<br>
Hearing a wimper in the back… Malaeliu rounded a corner and was beset on by the wounded Ogre, Kruuk, and a dozen little girls. Kruuk calmed them down and said the cleric would help. She healed their wounds, cast a calming spell on the frightened bunch and quietly led them out. The girls were still chained together, but Kruuk scooped them up into his arms and they successfully made it out the forest. <br>
<br>
Malaeliu showed them where to hide, asking the Stone Guardians to watch over them. They loyally obeyed.<br>
<br>
It was the light of the next day when Malaeliu went back to her home to pack her belongings. Entering her home, there was the High Council and Vri’dil standing in the midst of her room. The High Priest held out her broken necklace and asked her to explain herself. <br>
<br>
She told them everything, about Vri’dril’s corruption, the destruction of the children even guiding them to the hidden lair.<br>
<br>
Upon entry, the place was spotless. No evidence was found anywhere. Vri’dril took this moment to his advantage, calling Malaeliu to be banished as someone insane, not worthy of the Council. Malaehi cursed him to his face then screamed up to the sky cursing Innoruuk for being a weak Father of Lies.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kvael paused in the story, taking another drink of water. Peering around the Library halls, everyone was listening raptly. “ I ask that the elders consider the next page… and note that it was dated 3 months later… and written in by a hand of a child.” The elders murmured and nodded.<br>
<br>
“ Malaeliu was banished and punished so badly where she could no longer use her hands to write. We know she was released into the forests and the Stone Guardians took her body and the Ogre shaman and children nursed her back to life. Kruuk stayed with her and the children for a long time afterwards.<br>
<br>
The children were:<br>
<br>
Malaeli, a Teir'dal child<br>
Kaete, the barbarian child of the dead Shamaness. <br>
Malaehi a high elven waif.<br>
Malae, a human child<br>
Malaekru, an ogre<br>
Malaela, a troll<br>
Malaele, an erudite, the one we called Shai’le<br>
<br>
Please note - The story indicates that there were twelve girls saved, but the diary pages only mention these… but much is still incomplete.<br>
<br>
Malaeliu spend the rest of her days raising these girls teaching them to love each other and be a family. Like I said the rest of the diary was written by a child, with little stories of the sister’s antics and of the visitors who came to reclaim their lost children. <br>
<br>
Kaete’s family came for her, as did Malae’s. Kruuk decided to take Malaekru back home with him for his sisters to raise. Since Grobb was close he too Malaela back too. Malaehi, the high elf, was completely heartbroken to see them go, writing pages of how much she loved them and missed them.<br>
<br>
So, Malaehi- the high elf, Malaeli- the dark elf and our Erudite Malaele were left. And the diary ends here.<br>
<br>
Kvael pulled out papers from the shelf on the podium, and approached the Committee presenting them with more evidence of his research.<br>
<br>
Reports have it that Vri’dril gathered a group from Felwithe to raid Nektulos forest, in search of Malaeliu. In this report&quot; he waved in the air high &quot; Vri'dril accused Malaeliu of kidnapping the children!!&quot;<br>
<br>
He paused and shook his head, sadly.<br>
<br>
She was executed in front of the 3 girls. Witnesses say an enchantress wiped the memory of the girls, but the erudite got away. <br>
<br>
Malaehi was taken back to the High Elven city of Felwithe. The Ancients of Erollisi Marr adopted the child into their sect and she is serving with them still. She approaches her 20th season soon.<br>
<br>
A surprising turn of events... Vri’dril took the dark elven Malaeli into his home to raise her. She was brought up to be a priestess and honored for her bravery in battle. Interesting to note… one morning he and his household were all found dead, bodies where executed. Malaeli was never found and disappeared from all Norrathian records. She should be well into her 28th season, if she is still alive.<br>
<br>
As for the child of Erudin, Malaele, who we all called Shai’le... no one knows how she arrived back in our forests. But, her life was spent collecting these diary pages. And as you all witnessed, her life ended” he walked over to stand on the spot, “ right here.”<br>
<br>
The crowd was silent.<br>
<br>
After several minuted of silence, Elder Shotala cleared his throat. “ What would you do with this information now that you have it, Kvael?”<br>
<br>
“ In honor of the Mother’s wishes,&quot; he walked over and turned the diary to the first page, &quot; she wanted her daughters to share a name and a history. I think once the children come to the age of reasoning, in their 20th season of hunting, they should be invited here to hear this story.”<br>
<br>
The elders nodded in solemn agreement, and called the meeting to a close be cause of the late hour.<br>
<br>
Alone in the Library halls, Kvael sighed deeply and made a place for the Tome on the shelf, blew out the candles and walked home in silence.<br>
<br>
In memory of the Mother...<br>
